With a fixed, known supply, there is no money printer going brrrr, inflating away the value of your #BTC as with $USD. With a halving block reward at predetermined intervals, supply decreases programmatically over time. With the difficulty adjustment re-calibrating the... (13/25)

Fairness is an inherent feature of #BTC's monetary policy as well, baked into the protocol from its inception in 2009 and set in stone forever:

1. Fixed supply cap of 21M coins
2. Halving block reward every 4 years
3. The "difficulty adjustment" every 2 weeks

(12/25)

...#BTC's ledger is audited 24/7/365 and consensus is achieved on all transactions by thousands of independent, #decentralized nodes, which are cheap to set up and run, offering full transparency & equal voting rights. Miners do not control #BTC; nodes check that power. (11/25)

However, this is NOT how #BTC works. The amount of #BTC you hold has no bearing on your ability to effect changes to the protocol. Full stop. When you hear people say #BTC is #decentralized, they aren't talking about equal distribution of wealth. Instead, they meanğŸ‘‡ (10/25)

Next on my #progressive moral checklist is the issue of fairness/equal opportunity. Skeptics familiar with the Cantillon Effect may be inclined to think: "#BTC favors early adopters, it's too late for me, early money controls the game, & mining is expensive & centralized." (9/25)

This is in stark contrast to the $USD, which relies on trust in authority, oil, inequality, and military might to subsist. All fiat currencies, in fact, rely upon coercive threats of physical violence, enforced by oft corrupt regimes. These themes are antithetical to #BTC (7/25)

Among its benefits are, chiefly, that it is a system secured and maintained without violence. Instead, it utilizes a mechanism known as Proof-of-Work (#POW) whereby miners produce new #BTC by expending computational power to find a "nonce" fitting certain parameters. (5/25)

Given its inevitability, we can ask some normative questions: how should we deal with #BTC as a society? What benefits does it bestow and what challenges does it pose for the world? What are its externalities, and is it overall good for humanity? (4/25)
